isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.57) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.27. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.28, p < .001, 95% CI [12.98, 14.08]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.40, p = 0.746, 95% CI [-0.91, 0.65]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.21, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.49, S.E. = 0.32, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.12, -1.85]; Std. beta = -0.56, 95% CI [-0.71, -0.42])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -3.39, S.E. = 0.46, p < .001, 95% CI [-4.29, -2.49]; Std. beta = -0.77, 95% CI [-0.97, -0.56])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.94, S.E. = 0.49, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.90, -1.99]; Std. beta = -0.67, 95% CI [-0.88, -0.45])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.47, S.E. = 0.67, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.78, -1.16]; Std. beta = -0.56, 95% CI [-0.86, -0.26])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
